=== Experiment 4: the synchronous_commit ladder — Fri Jul 24 09:33:08 SAST 2026 ===

--- step 1: the table under test, and the pgbench script (one INSERT per transaction) ---

$ psql@primary -c "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS ledger; CREATE TABLE ledger (id serial PRIMARY KEY, payload text);"
NOTICE:  table "ledger" does not exist, skipping
DROP TABLE
CREATE TABLE
$ cat /tmp/bench.sql
INSERT INTO ledger (payload) VALUES ('x');

--- step 2: before — no synchronous standby is named, so both replicas are async ---

$ psql@primary -c "SHOW synchronous_standby_names;"
 synchronous_standby_names 
---------------------------
 
(1 row)


$ psql@primary -c "SELECT application_name, sync_state FROM pg_stat_replication ORDER BY application_name;"
 application_name | sync_state 
------------------+------------
 sba              | async
 sbb              | async
(2 rows)


--- step 3: name standby A as the synchronous standby ---

$ psql@primary -c "ALTER SYSTEM SET synchronous_standby_names = 'sba'; SELECT pg_reload_conf();"
ERROR:  ALTER SYSTEM cannot run inside a transaction block

$ psql@primary -c "SELECT application_name, sync_state FROM pg_stat_replication ORDER BY application_name;"
 application_name | sync_state 
------------------+------------
 sba              | async
 sbb              | async
(2 rows)

Standby A is now sync; standby B remains async and is never waited on.

